        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Absolutely yes! Pune to Mumbai Airport is 150 km. Our Kia Carens EV has 452 km real-world range and BYD E-MAX 7 has 530 km range. That means you'll arrive with 65-70% battery still remaining. We've completed 500+ trips without a single mid-journey charging stop."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the real-world range of electric cabs?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Real-world range (actual driving) is 85-90% of ARAI-claimed range. Kia Carens EV: ARAI 452 km ‚Üí Real-world 380-400 km. BYD E-MAX 7: ARAI 530 km ‚Üí Real-world 450-480 km. Factors like AC usage, speed, and weather reduce range by 10-15% from claimed figures."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What factors affect electric vehicle range?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Main factors: Speed (faster = more drain), AC/heating usage (reduces 10-15%), weather (cold/hot affects battery), driving style (aggressive braking wastes energy), terrain (uphill uses more, downhill regenerates), passenger load (heavier = more consumption), and tire pressure (low pressure increases drag)."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does AC reduce electric car range significantly?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "AC usage reduces range by 10-15% (about 40-50 km on 400 km range). However, this is already factored into our planning. On Pune-Mumbai (150 km), even with AC on full, you'll still have 200+ km range remaining at arrival. Modern EV AC systems are very efficient."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does regenerative braking work in EV cabs?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Regenerative braking converts kinetic energy back into electricity when slowing down. Instead of wasting energy as heat (like regular brakes), EVs send power back to battery. On Pune-Mumbai ghats (Lonavala hills), regen braking can recover 15-20 km of range during downhill sections."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens if EV cab battery runs low during journey?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "This has never happened in our 500+ trips (we always maintain 40%+ buffer). If it hypothetically did: EV would enter 'turtle mode' (reduced power but still drivable), we'd use DC fast charging stations on route (30 min for 200+ km), multiple charging stations exist between Pune-Mumbai, and professional drivers monitor battery constantly."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is EV range affected by passenger weight and luggage?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, but minimally. Extra 300 kg (4 passengers + luggage) reduces range by approximately 3-5% (12-20 km on 400 km range). For Pune-Mumbai, this means arrival battery drops from 65% to 60% - still very safe margin. Weight impact is much less than in diesel cars."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How accurate are EV range displays?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Modern EV range displays (like in Kia Carens and BYD E-MAX 7) are very accurate, typically within 5-10%. They calculate based on recent driving patterns, current battery state, AC usage, and terrain. Our drivers trust the display and it has proven reliable in 500+ trips."
      }
    }
  ]
};
